5: Osteoporosis

The hyperparathyroidism causes bone resorption.
Despite normal calcium levels in osteoporotic patients, because of the mechanism above, dietary calcium supplementation can offset the body's need to resorb bone.

  • -2.5 to -1 => Osteopenia
  • Oestrogen deficiency is a major factor in the producing accelerated bone loss. (Oestrogen deficieny can be caused by anorexia nervosa and in athletes)

It measures bone density per square area, NOT per unit volume. Even so, it is very accurate.
Nitrogen containing and non nitrogen containing

nitrogen containing

Most of the ones we know.

non nitrogen

Chlordronate
tilodronoate

They all limit osteoclast bone resorption.
Bisphosphonate binds to hydroxoapetite and inhibits bone mineralization -> can cause osteomalacia (most prominent with non nitrogen containing bisphonates).
Have poor oral absorption -> further impaired by food and drink and drugs ==containing calclium, magnesium, etc==.

Indications: osteoporosis, pagets disease of bone, hypercalcaemi of malignancy and metastatic bone disease.
In maligngncy, bisophonates reduced the risk of fracture. (won't prevent bone metz.)

    lithium levels must be done before lithium dose is given. (? trough levels)
  • It passes into cells via the sodium channels but is not pumped out via Na/K ATPase so accumulates within neurons.
  • Half of the oral dose is eliminated quickly by the kidneys. The rest is eliminated slowly over 2 weeks.
    • Lithium levels can be increased by hyponatremia because "the kidney treats lithium and sodium similarly and hyponatremia will cause increased lithium reabsorption" in the proximal tubule.
    • Diuretics acting distal to the PCT have a similar effect.
    • Side effects occuring at therapeutic range: Fine tremor, polyuria, polydypsia, metallic taste, goiter, hypothyroidism, weight gain, oedema, diabetes insipidus and arrhythmias
    • Moderate toxicity : (plasma level > 1.5mmo/L) - GI: N/V/D and neuromuscular: Course tremor, weakness, ataxia, blurred vision
    • Severe toxicity: Medical emergency: hyperreflexia, hyperextension of limbs, convulsions, syncope and death.
    • Drugs interfering with renal excretion of lithium: Thiazides > loop diuretics, ACEi, ARB, NSAIDS,

Regulation of gastric acid secretion

parietal means "of the wall"

Acid is Secreted by parietal cells. Parietal cells are present in glands within the fundus and body of the stomach.

Parietal cells express histamine H2-type receptors, muscarinic M3 receptors, and gastrin/CCK-2 or B-type receptors.

1. **Gastrin** is the major endocrine regulator of the secretory response.
2. Secreted in reponse to *gastric distention* and *amino acids* (and *vagal* stimulation)
3. **Gastrin** from **G cells** in the ***antrum of the pylorus***  stimulates *histamine* release from *ECL cells* (fundic glands)-> *histamine* stimulates acid secretion from parietal cells (via the **endocrine route**)
5. Gastrin also **directly acts** on the parietal cells to increase acid secretion.
1. **Somatostatin** - **potent anti acid hormone**. Secreted by ***D cells*** located throughout gastric mucosa and from *oxyntic glands.* It *inhibits histamine* release -> *reduces parietal cell acid production*.
2. **Histamine** - Secreted from  ECL cells, *located in close proximity* to the parietal cells. It Binds **~~H1~~H2** receptor and promotes acid secretion. Activate adenyl cyclase -> incr. cAMP (vascular cells have H2 receptors which are not activated at this concentration)
  1. Cephalic - ACh
    Cimetidine - enzyme inhibitor, can cause gynaecomastia.

Cauda equina symdrome

Usually caused by a disc prolapse; but neoplasms can also present this way.

[!INFO] Spinal cord terminates at L1/L2.

  • Faecal incontinence with reduced rectal sphincter tone
  • Erectile dysfunction
  • Areflexia - Lower motor neurons are affected

The cauda equina is made up of the ascending and descending nerve roots from L2 to the coccygeal segments. It is responsible for lower limb movement and sensation, bladder control/urination, external anal sphincter control and defecation, sexual function - (causes erectile dysfunction), and sensation of the genitalia and perineal region. Commonest cause is disk prolapse. Source

[!INFO] Whipples disease

  • Tropheryma whippeli - gram Positive Rod, PAS positive. Ubiquitous in environment.
  • Classical features: (arthralgias, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and weight loss)
  • Multisystemic disease; Migratory arthralgias precede other features by years.
  • Later, intermittant diarrhoea with abdominal pain and wasting.
  • CNS: cognitive impairment and dementia.
  • Endocarditis.
  • Typically affects white males.
  • Suspect in RF negative migratory polyarthritis.
  • Treatment: Initially penicillin or ceftriaxone to penetrate blood brain barrier followed by TMP-SMX for 12 months.
  - Other streptococci - **bovis**
  • Staph aureus - *usually not penicillin sensitive; so penicillin is not appropriate.
    • For Streptococci, penicillin + gentamicin combination is used (because it's synergistic) even if they organisms are resistant to penicillin.
      Indications - valve dysfunction causing heart failure, persistent infection, intracardiac abscess
  1. Atrial fibrillation
  2. Sepsis - low cardiac perfusion / sepsis induced myocardial depression
  3. Renal failure
  4. Stroke or SAH - increased / unstable autonomic output to the heart.
  5. Chronic kidney disease - due to myocardial structural abnormalities in CKD.
    1. Infiltrative diseases - amyloidosis
    2. Implantable cardioverter-defibrillator shocks / cardioversion
